  "nodes": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/fea-predicts-compression-bending",
      "type": "Claim",
      "name": "FEA model adequately predicts ASTM F1717 compression-bending behavior of non-cannulated pedicle screw construct",
      "description": "The FEA modeling framework, comprising meshing procedures validated per ASME V&V 10 guidelines, material property assignments derived from published titanium alloy data (ASTM F136), and boundary conditions consistent with ASTM F1717 fixture geometry, has been shown through extensive internal benchmarking and three independent analyst teams (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) to reproduce construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement within the pre-established acceptance bounds. The convergence study documented in the model development report confirms mesh-independent solutions at element sizes below 0.4 mm in the screw-rod interface region. Material nonlinearity is captured via a bilinear isotropic hardening model calibrated against coupon test data. Across all three quantities of interest and all 11 experimental specimens spanning two independent laboratories, the model predictions fall within 10% of experimental means and the normalized validation metric E/uval remains below 1.96, satisfying both acceptance criteria stipulated in the validation plan. This claim synthesizes the totality of the verification, validation, and uncertainty quantification activities documented in the supporting model development and validation reports."
    }
  ],
